As now we have to take all the weather varibles into our model thus we shall now create a new weather file integrating all the the weather files. Combining all the weather files into a single file 2011-11-01 TO 2015-02-28 You can also embed plots, for example:

completeFile <- function(directory,id = 1:4){
  files_list <- list.files(directory,full.names = TRUE)
  dat <- data.frame()
  for( i in id){
    dat <- rbind(dat,read.table(files_list[i],header = TRUE,sep = ",",
                                fill = TRUE))
  }
  dat$timestamp <- as.numeric(as.POSIXct(dat$EST, format="%Y-%m-%d"))
  dat
}

We still need to define either we are working for HDD or CDD i.e. either heating energy consumption or cooling energy consumption Thus we can actually convert the temperature to HDD and CDD values which will help us to work with temoerature.

HDD To calculate HDD, take the average of a day’s high and low temperatures and subtract from 65. For example, if the day’s average temperature is 50o F, its HDD is 15. If every day in a 30-day month had an average temperature of 50o F, the month’s HDD value would be 450 (15 x 30).source -wikipedia

Now we will add a new predictable variable HDD(Heating Degree Days) for all the all the values of the timestamp. 65 F will be the cutoff temperature. If the mean temperature is above the cutoff we dont have heating degree days that day.

weather$HDD <- abs(weather$Mean.TemperatureF - 65)
# Thus we can either ignore the HDD values. Topic for discussion.
# We can take either of the HDD or CDD(Cooling Degree Day) depending 
# we are investigating heating or cooling energy consumption).

# If the mean temperature is above 65, there are no heating degree
# days that day.
# Extracting the values which have the mean temp is below 65
weatherHDD <- filter(weather,
                     (weather$Mean.TemperatureF < 65))

library("base")
# Creating a new column which will represent the day for the given
# time stamp so what we can work on the values for weekdays energy
# as the building we are aiming to analyse is the Student Services.
buildingWeather$Days <- weekdays(as.POSIXct(buildingWeather$timestamp, origin="1970-01-01"))
buildingWeatherWeekdays <- filter(buildingWeather,
                                  buildingWeather$Days == "Monday" |
                                    buildingWeather$Days == "Tuesday"|
                                    buildingWeather$Days == "Wednesday" |
                                    buildingWeather$Days == "Thursday" |
                                    buildingWeather$Days == "Friday")
buildingWeatherWeekends <- filter(buildingWeather,
                                  buildingWeather$Days == "Saturday"|
                                    buildingWeather$Days == "Sunday")
# Now we have two data frames for weekdays and weekends and thus
